Observation Details: *High Count - Minimum. Encounters with NSWO at 4 distinct locations. Site 1) Heard and saw perched 1 owl on our way to the fields at the second field, and heard an owl on the way back at the first field, both times coming from the same patch of woods, so can assume 1 owl. Site 2) Heard twice and saw a flyover of an owl on the trail through Spencer Brook, noting streaking underneath, small size, and response to whistle. First heard at the start of the trail, and then again about 2/5ths of the way down the trail, accompanied by the flyover. Assumed second owl. Site 3) Heard multiple times along E/SE edge of Newbury Field/woods, in the young pines. Responding to whistled imitation. First heard right after entering Newbury field, and once again further down the trail, accompanied by a flyover. Heard again at the second spot on the way back. Could have been 2 birds, but better to assume 1, making this the third owl. Site 4) Heard multiple times and seen once on the SW edge of Newbury Field, once again in dense cluster of younger pines, the fourth owl. It seemed like there could have been more, as the encounters at sites 2 and 3 were somewhat spaced out. But I feel that the 4 Sites were distinct enough to assume that there were 4 separate owls, at least.

La semaine dernière, nous avons eu la chance d'entendre un mâle chanter. Il semblait être perché tout près sur le bord du chemin. Suite à cette découverte, nous y sommes retourné la semaine suivante afin d'étudier le type d'habitat qu'il utilisait. Juste avant notre départ, je remarque une cavité qui m'inspire énormément. Je me suis dis que si j'étais une petite nyctale j'aimerais bien l'habiter. J'ai donc pris mon courage entre les mains et marché sur la neige. Avant même que je sois rendu à l'arbre je jette un oeil et voie cette jolie petite face avec ses deux beaux yeux jaunes.

Media notes: Ruffed Grouse

Observation Details: A nearly unbelievable find! The grouse was first found this morning and then relocated this evening along the entrance road about 100m west of the Quarry Trailhead entrance. As I walked along the road towards the group supposedly watching the grouse I was looking in the bushes on both sides of the road, searching for any sign of the grouse. To my great surprise, the Ruffed Grouse was actually sitting on the concrete barrier on the side of the road less than five feet away from the group. As I got out my camera to take some photos the grouse actually walked towards me and got even closer until it was only about two feet away. Many thanks to Melissa Hafting for refinding the bird and then waiting with it until I arrived so I could find it so easily. It seems ridiculous, but Ruffed Grouse has been a bird that I've been looking for for more than five years; I've been all over B.C. and even to Ontario in my search, and I've been as close as hearing them fly away from me only a few metres away on multiple occasions, so to finally see my lifer Ruffed Grouse actually in Vancouver and in such a remarkable manner is really as special as it gets.

This individual was possibly seen yesterday on the Seekonk River in Providence by Michael Morin and is making its way back out of the bay (See this checklist). With a dumpy posture, wings held slightly lowered the bird might be injured (possibly missing tail/undertail feathers) and could be incapable of flight, although it is alert and apparently swimming well and covering some good mileage... It could very well just be gathering strength after the recent storms and high winds.

Observation Details: Arrived with Black-caps, small triangle of white in fore-cheeks unlike broad white cheek of Black-caps. Crown brown, bib black and abbreviated (shorter) than Black-caps. Back dark brown; flanks with orange-brown. Lower, husky calls. Eye dark.  This is my second Boreal Chickadee in Kennebec county, the first having been in Sidney on a Waterville CBC (14 December 2008). That bird was found after doggedly searching for the species all day. That was the only time I have tried to see if a Boreal Chickadee could be found in winter here. The count had one previous record for 19 December 1993. I suspect a few occur almost annually in or near conifer patches in winter throughout this region, which is outside their breeding range, and they might be more routine in the region compared to the species' irregular occurrences to s. New England, for example. Some of those movements involve birds that appear to return to the same sites several winters consecutively.

Just amazing. Four in view at once at Triplets Bridge -- three actively feeding, probing deep in the mud and under the snow (saw them nab the occasional worm!), and one roosting in the sun near a rock, not moving the whole time I was there. The bird in the picture briefly flew out of the stream and onto the snow, where it entertained the crowd with its wiggle walk. Then, at the Oven and the stream leading into it, I had at least four birds -- perhaps more, but the birds in the area were being flushed repeatedly by a pair of immature Red-tailed Hawks, one of whom was finishing up a woodcock meal when I arrived. There was a second pile of feathers nearby. Apparently the park's raptors were having quite the feast -- other observers were relating stories of multiple birds being taken by hawks and falcons throughout the day. Birds were reported in double digits over the last couple of days. According to eBird and word of mouth, nothing like this has been recorded here in recent memory. Apparently the late heavy snow coincided with woodcock migration and left them nowhere to hide. Hope most of them make it out alive.

Observation Details: A nearly unbelievable find! The grouse was first found this morning and then relocated this evening along the entrance road about 100m west of the Quarry Trailhead entrance. As I walked along the road towards the group supposedly watching the grouse I was looking in the bushes on both sides of the road, searching for any sign of the grouse. To my great surprise, the Ruffed Grouse was actually sitting on the concrete barrier on the side of the road less than five feet away from the group. As I got out my camera to take some photos the grouse actually walked towards me and got even closer until it was only about two feet away. Many thanks to Melissa Hafting for refinding the bird and then waiting with it until I arrived so I could find it so easily. It seems ridiculous, but Ruffed Grouse has been a bird that I've been looking for for more than five years; I've been all over B.C. and even to Ontario in my search, and I've been as close as hearing them fly away from me only a few metres away on multiple occasions, so to finally see my lifer Ruffed Grouse actually in Vancouver and in such a remarkable manner is really as special as it gets.

Super, super, super cool--both sexes observed constructing this nest cavity. Yes, spring indeed has arrived to Anchorage! This is quite a scarce resident in the Municipality of Anchorage and it is exciting to confirm a nesting attempt. According to Dave Sonneborn, it's been maybe about 15 years since there was a known nest in the Anchorage area. Interestingly, the nest cavity is only approximately 6 feet above ground. In an Oregon study by C. D. Forristal where 210 nests were sampled, the minimum height found was 8.9 feet.  I am almost always one to be very forthcoming with bird locations, but for now I am going to leave this one undisclosed. The cavity is far from completed and I would imagine they are much more likely to abandon it at this stage rather than once nesting has initiated. I myself have no intentions of returning anytime soon either.

Trois filles au Pays des Merveilles  Les étoiles tourbillonnent dans l'air calme de la nuit. Le jour était déjà loin derrière et les brindilles déjà séchées, tentant de survivre à l'automne, ne dansaient plus dans les clairières qui bordent la forêt.  C'est alors que, bien modestement, trois filles sortent discrètement de leur carrosse. Elles sont bien miniatures dans ce monde dominé par les grands arbres. L'automne avancée, il ne reste plus de feuilles dans les arbres. Du haut de leur piédestal, elles sont maintenant toutes allongées sur le sol. Dans plusieurs semaines, d'autres viendront redonner la couleur rendant reconnaissable chaque espèces qui se dressent devant elles.  Quel spectacle agréable que ce ciel étoilé! La Voie Lactée est vite remarquée, et quelques étoiles jalouses s'affirment et filent du nord au sud, d'est en ouest pour le plaisir de nos yeux.  -Hou-hou- hou.... Une première voix se fait entendre. Une Chouette rayée veux nous faire honneur. -Hou- hou hou ..... Puis une deuxième!!! Direction opposée. Tactique habituelle, les trois filles, après une longue discussion regagnent leur carrosse et avec confiance, elles se déplace vers l'un des oiseaux. C'est la déroute! Plus rien! L'équipe regagne donc leur monture et nerveusement tente de localiser l'autre oiseau. La patrouille s’arrête, et bien ....renversement de situation! Mais qui oserait critiquer ce changement! Un auxiliaire a pris la relève! C'est maintenant un Grand-Duc d'Amérique qui carillonne au loin! Un heureux mélange d'espèces qui s'annonce en ce début de soirée! Mais il n'est pas seul,car à l'opposé du sentier, un deuxième lui retourne quelques compliments sur son couplet bien interprété. Gourmande, les trois filles exercent leurs droits à l'écoute de plusieurs refrains. En dépit que l'opéra n'est pas encore terminé, les trois filles remontent en selle et s'engagent dans le territoire d'une amie bien connue, la Chouette rayée. Cette amie a trader à se pointer, mais elle n'a pas manquée de culot en arrivant, rasant le sol, pour ensuite effectuer un virage serré et terminer sa course dans un arbre limitant toute localisation. Mais, bien en voix, elle a bien voulue interpréter quelques couplets. Enchantement pour les oreilles.  Politesse oblige, les trois filles laissent leur hôte et vont maintenant vers le nord. Peu exploré, les trois exploratrices ne savent pas trop à quoi s'attendre. Pour ne rien manquer, elles décident de commencer par le commencement, donc la fin du chemin! Encore plus radieuses, les étoiles tentent encore une fois de voler la vedette. Inutile. Car la vedette est là! Possédant toute sa confiance, elle se dresse devant les trois filles qui se se sentent comme des petites Princesses à qui l'on offre un cadeau sur un beau coussin rouge!!!! Son petit bec jaune accompagne ses magnifiques yeux! Son petit ''V'' sur le front lui donne un petit air sévère, mais nul ne s'en plaint. Elle se dresse toute gracieuse sur une petite branche à une hauteur parfaite.  Les trois filles se gavent de l'observation qui se présente, tel un cornet de crème glacée lors d'une chaude journée. La Nyctale se laissera t'elle emporté vers le sud? Le Pays des Merveilles sera t'il le sien pour l'hiver?

Observation Details: While listening for owls in a small subalpine forest clearing Alex heard chattering that ended up being a flying squirrel on a snag directly above us. Looking back down at us was this female boreal owl. At one point she showed a pink brood patch, making this the first confirmed record of boreal owls using a natural nest cavity in Washington state. Alex Patia and Ryan Merrill saw it again on 6/24 but it was not seen again after that. Habitat was mature mountain hemlock and Engelmann spruce quite a ways below tree line with lots of snow still on the ground.

My record of this encounter, written from memory, is as follows: As I was walking alone through the bog, no more than a few hundred feet north of the boardwalk, I heard what sounded like a small group of chickadees making agitated scolding calls. I suspected a shrike (some small part of my mind secretly hoping for something like a Saw-whet) and went to investigate. My heart just about stopped when I caught sight of a smallish bulge beside a relatively thick spruce trunk, overall about the same color as the bark, some distance ahead. The echo of this moment is recorded on my phone as, "I JUST FOUND A BOREAL OWL" "TELL NO ONE"; none of my words can reproduce it in full. I recall thinking that it looked more like the Boreal Owl depicted on the Wilbert Cafe placemat than the one at the Admiral Rd. feeders last winter. Apparently this owl had been found and reported by at least one other person earlier in the day, but I had no knowledge of this at the time I first found it; someone texted me a screenshot of the separate report on Telegram a short time later. Dad came quietly hurrying over, and we stood in a little shadow of ecstasy for some time. We never came closer than perhaps about 20 to 25 feet away from the owl. At the approach of other hikers, we moved away so as not to draw suspicion, and Dad went back to the car. As I was walking back toward the owl's location a short time later, I caught sight of it as it leaned forward and zipped away into the trees. A bit giddy with my second instance of lottery-winning luck within the past hour, I went back to the boardwalk.   A bit later I was looking around in the area where the owl had seemed to go, and, sure enough, I was able to relocate it. I found a convenient viewing spot a respectful distance away and spent some more time enjoying this little manifestation of nothing less than God's goodness. At the approach of a pair of birders on the boardwalk, one of whom turned out to be Erik Bruhnke, I approached them and asked if they could keep a secret. Soon I was sharing this incredible sighting with them, and joy was on all our faces. I believe the owl finally flew off a second time before we left, all grateful for this amazing sighting.
